.pl 62
                            Chapter 2


              ELEMENTS OF DSI-32 ASSEMBLY LANGUAGE


2.1  INTRODUCTION

This  chapter  describes certain aspects of the  DSI-32  Assembly 
Language.

2.2  CHARACTER SET

The  DSI-32  assembler  supports a subset of the  standard  ASCII 
character set.

 - Upper and lower-case letters A through Z.
 - Digits 0 through 9.
 - Blanks , Tabs.
 - The following printable characters:

Character  Name                      Character  Name
---------  ----                      ---------  ----
   '       Apostrophe                    +      Plus Sign
   (       Left Parentheses              /      Slash
   )       Right Parentheses             :      Colon
   .       Period                        ;      Semi-Colon
   _       Underscore                    @      At Sign
   ,       Comma                         [      Left Square Bracket
   -       Minus Sign and/or Hyphen      ]      Right Square Bracket
   *       Asterisk                      "      Double Quote
   %       Percent   
Carriage Return serves as the line terminator.
The  entire  ASCII  character set is permitted when  enclosed  in 
quotes.

The  Assembler differentiates between upper and lower  case  user 
defined  symbol names but all other mnemonics and register  names 
are not case sensitive.
.pa
2.3  DSI-32 ASSEMBLER STATEMENTS

DSI-32  Assembler statements must follow a  specific  syntactical 
format which is described in detail below:

  [<label>:[: | -]] [<mnemonic> [<operands>]] [;<comment>]

description:

<label>
     the label is generally optional but certain pseudo ops  such 
     as 'EQU' require the label to be present.  Labels follow the 
     rules for valid symbol names.  A label  must  be immediately 
     followed by either one,  two colons,  or a colon and a minus 
     sign.   The label will be assigned the value and type of the 
     current  relocation mode unless  the pseudo op was 'EQU'  in 
     which  case the expression following the 'EQU' is  evaluated 
     and the resultant type and value is assigned to the label.

<mnemonic>
     is an optional 32000 instruction or Assembler pseudo-op.  If 
     no mnemonic is present then the comment character or the end 
     of line character must be present.

<operands>
     the  operands of the  instruction  follow the mnemonic.  The 
     number of operands  required depend on the mnemonic. If more 
     or   less operands are supplied the assembler will issue  an 
     error.  Operands  must  be separated by the comma  character 
     (,).  Spaces  may be used to add clarity to   the    program   
     but   are otherwise ignored. An operand is illegal without a 
     valid mnemonic.

<comment>
     is  the optional comment.  A comment must be preceded by the 
     semi-colon character (;).  All characters after the  comment 
     character are ignored by the assembler.

A source line of 32000 Assembler code must follow the following:

 -   Multiple statements are not permitted on the same line.
 -   A statement may begin in any column.
 -   A statement must no be longer than 132 characters.

Examples:

  1.         FLAG           ;a single instruction only
  2.         BR    STOPT
  3.         ADDW  R7, R3   ;add register R7 to R3
  4.  LABEL:                ;just a label
  5.  STOP:  ADDB  R0, R2   ;add register R0 to R2
2.4  STRING AND NUMBER SYNTAX
	
The  DSI-32 assembler supports three basic formats for constants: 
one for integer values,  one for floating-point values,  and  one 
for strings.

2.4.1  Integer Format

An integer  has the following form:

    [<sign>] [<base>] <digits>

description:

     <sign>              specifies  the sign of the integer.  The 
                         default positive value may be overridden 
                         by  prepending  the  (-)  sign  to   the 
                         integer. 

     <base>              specifies  the  number  base  which  the
                         integer   is  to  be  defined  in.   The
                         following number bases are supported  by
                         the DSI-32 assembler:
		   Binary      -  B'
		   Octal       -  O' or Q'
		   Decimal     -  D'
		   Hexadecimal -  H' or X'
		   Decimal is the default number base.

     <digits>            used to specify the integer.  The digits 
                         must be valid for the selected base:
		   Binary      -  0 through 1
		   Octal       -  0 through 7
		   Decimal     -  0 through 9
		   Hexadecimal -  0 through 9 and A through F
				  (or lower case a through f)

Integer  constants have the following range of values,  depending 
on their size:  -128 to 127 for signed byte constants,  0 to  255 
for   unsigned  constants,   -32678  to  32767  for  signed  word 
constants, 0 to 65535 for unsigned word constants, -2147483648 to 
2147483647 (-2**31 to 2**31-1) for double-word constants.

Examples:

   Binary         Octal          Decimal          Hexadecimal
   ------         -----          -------          -----------
  -B'01          -Q'3027          -121            -X'124E
   B'10011011     O'034          D'2139            H'231A
  +B'101         +Q'225           +12232          +H'1AB2
.pa
2.4.2  Floating-Point Number Syntax

Floating point numbers have the following form:

                Mantissa                 Exponent
  ------------------------------ ----------------------
  [<sign>] <digits> {.[<digits>] [E [<sign>] <digits> ] |
                     [.<digits>]  E [<sign>] <digits>}

description:

     <sign>              specifies the sign of the floating point 
                         number. The default positive sign may be 
                         overridden by the (-) sign. 

     <digits>            Only   decimal    digits  are  permitted 
                         (0  to  9).   The decimal point must  be 
                         preceded be at least one digit.

     .                   the decimal point.

     E                   When the 'E' character is specified then 
                         an exponent field is then required.  The 
                         maximum   size   of  the   exponent   is 
                         determined  by  the size of the  number. 
                         ie.  whether  it is a single  or  double 
                         precision number. 

Examples:

  Valid          Invalid        Comments
  -----          -------        --------
  281.            -0.A12        ;decimal digits only
  +1.1E-12        +0.125E777    ;exponent exceeds limit
  80E+21           100          ;either decimal point or exponent
                                ;flag required.

NOTE:     The DSI-32 Assembler recognizes two sizes of  floating-
          point  constant:   single-precision (float) and double-
          precision     (long).      Single-precision     numbers           
          occupy  four  bytes of memory.   The  largest  positive           
          single-precision value is 3.40282346E38;  the  smallest           
          positive value is 1.17549430E-38.  The largest negative                     
          value   is   the  negative  value  is   -3.40282346E38.           
          Double-precision numbers occupy eight bytes of  memory.            
          The   largest   positive  double-precision  number   is           
          1.79769313486231305E308.  The largest negative value is           
          -1.79769313486231305E308.    The   assembler   performs           
          minimal  checking of floating point numbers thus it  is           
          the user's responsibility to enter legal numbers only.
.pa
2.4.3  String Syntax

Strings have the following form:

  '[<ASCII string>...]'
         or
  "[<ASCII string>...]"

The Assembler treats quotes within strings in a special way:

   - Strings  which  contain  single quotes may  be  enclosed  in 
     double quotes
   - Strings  which  contain  double quotes may  be  enclosed  in 
     single quotes
   - Strings  enclosed  in  double quotes  which  contain  double 
     quotes  must specify the double quotes within the string  by 
     the use of two double quotes
   - Strings  enclosed  in  single quotes  which  contain  single 
     quotes  must specify the single quotes within the string  by 
     the use of two single

The instruction or pseudo-op controls both the maximum length and 
the way in which a string is stored in memory.

Examples:

   Strings in Source Statements           Resultant String 
   ----------------------------           ----------------
      "this is a test string"             this is a test string
      'another one'                       another one
      "Don't do that"                     Don't do that
      'the letter "a"'                    the letter "a"
      "the letter ""a"""                  the letter "a"
.pa
2.5  SYMBOLS

Symbols are names used to refer to user defined constants, labels 
and  re-defined  register names.  Symbols have  three  parameters 
associated with them:  a unique name,  a value, and a type. There 
are  various symbols which are reserved by the assembler such  as 
instruction mnemonics,  pseudo-ops etc.  Reserved symbols may not 
be redefined by the user. A complete list of all reserved symbols 
used by the DSI-32 Assembler may be found in Appendix C.

A user defined symbol must follow the following rules:

   - the  first  character  must by a letter (A - Z  or  a  - z), 
     underscore character (_) or the percent character (%).
     N.B. Symbols are case sensitive.
   - any remaining characters may be letters, digits, '_' or '.'
   - the  name must be unique to the first 8 characters  for  the      
     National   Semiconductor  NSX  compatible  DSI-32  assembler      
     and  to  the  first 29 characters for  the  extended  DSI-32      
     assembler.

Examples:

  Valid          Invalid        Comments
  -----          -------        --------
  label          @LABEL         ; @ is an illegal character
  _TEST          2TIMES         ;first character cannot be a digit
  L1234          SP             ;SP is reserved symbol

User  defined symbols must only be defined once within a program. 
There are three ways of defining symbols:

 - by defining a label in front of a mnemonic
 - by use the EQU pseudo-op
 - by the use of the IMPORT or IMPORTP pseudo-ops.

For the first way:

	  <symbol name>:  <statement>
    or    <symbol name>:: <statement>
    or    <symbol name>:- <statement>

All  three cases result in the symbol being assigned the type  of 
the  location  counter (see Section 2.7).  The second  case  also 
exports the symbol, while the third case both imports and exports 
the symbol.
.pa
For the second way:

   <symbol name>: EQU  <expression>

The  symbol is assigned the value and type of  the  <expression>.  
The values allowed for <expression> depend on the symbol type.

For the third way:

	IMPORT <symbol name>,,,
               or
	IMPORTP <symbol name>,,,

These two cases are only for use with external  symbols.  Section 
5.6  describes the IMPORT and IMPORTP pseudo-ops in  detail.  The 
extended DSI-32 assembler also will implicitly define a symbol if 
a  symbol is used with a CXP instruction eg  CXP  UNDEFINED.  The 
symbol  UNDEFINED  in  the  above example would  be  defined  and 
imported.
.pa
2.6  SYMBOL TYPES

A Symbol or expression may have one of the following types:

   - Immediate            - SB Relative
   - External             - FP Relative
   - Long                 - SP Relative
   - Register             - PC Relative
   - Absolute             - Undefined

The type of a symbol specifies when symbol may be permitted as an 
operand and how it is used.  The assembler displays the type of a 
symbol  with  a  two letter abbreviation if  a  cross  referenced 
listing is requested. 


2.6.1  Immediate

The Immediate type specifies a 32 bit, signed Integer:

The two letter abbreviation for Immediate type is IM. Below is an 
example:

   TEST1     00000043   IM     ;an integer with the value 67
   TEST2     FFFFFFA0   IM     ;an integer with the value -96


2.6.2  Long

The  Long  type  specifies either a single  or  double  precision 
floating point constant.

The two letter abbreviation for Long type type is LN.   Below  is 
an example:

  FRED      412442422424E50   LN


2.6.3  Register

The  Register type is assigned to a symbol which has been equated 
to  either a general purpose register (R<n>) or a  Floating-Point 
register (F<n>) where n is a number 0 to 7.

The two letter abbreviation for Register type is RG.  Below is an 
example:

  START        R7   RG
  FPRES        F6   RG

.pa
2.6.4  Absolute

The  Absolute type is assigned to symbols which refer to absolute 
memory locations.

The two letter abbreviation for absolute type is AB.  Below is an 
example:

  LOCN         00000133   AB

The   '@'  character  is used to inform the  assembler  that  the 
resulting expression value is to be given the absolute type.

   @ <disp>

where  <disp> is an expression which must evaluate to a value  in 
the  range 0 through 16777215 (this is a limitation if the  32032 
CPU;  16777215 = 2**24-1) with Immediate type.


2.6.5  External

The  External type is assigned to symbols (or expressions)  whose 
addresses are pointed to by a link table entry and an offset.

The two letter abbreviation for External type is EX.  Below is an 
example:

   TEST        00000012   0000001A   EX

In this example,  the first integer specifies the 18th  (starting 
from  zero)  Link Table entry,  the second integer  specifies  an 
offset of 26 from the address at the 18th entry.

The format for specifying an External type is:

  EXT (<disp1>)[+<disp2>]

where  <disp1> is an expression which must evaluate to a value in 
the  range 0 through 16777215 with Immediate  type,  and  <disp2> 
must  be in the range -16777215 through 16777215.  <disp1> is the 
Link Table entry number and <disp2> is the optional offset.
.pa
2.6.6  SB Relative

The SB relative type is assigned to symbols which refer to memory 
locations defined relative to the SB register.

The two letter abbreviation for SB relative type is SB.  Below is 
a listing format example:

  TEST1         00000123  SB

The SB relative type has the following form:

  <disp> (SB)

where  <disp>  is a constant or expression which evaluates  to  a 
value in the range -16777215 to 16777215 with Immediate type.

2.6.7  FP Relative

The FP relative type is assigned to symbols which refer to memory 
locations defined relative to the FP register.

The abbreviation for FP relative type is FP.   below is a listing 
format example:

  TEST1         00000123   FP

The FP relative type has the following form:

  <disp> (FP)

where  <disp>  is a constant or expression which evaluates  to  a 
value in the range -16777215 to 16777215 with Immediate type.

2.6.8  SP Relative

The SP relative type is assigned to symbols which refer to memory 
locations defined relative to the SP register.

The two letter abbreviation for SP relative type is SP.  Below is 
a listing format example:

  TEST1        0000123   SP

The SP relative type has the following form:

  <disp> (SP)

where  <disp>  is a constant or expression which evaluates  to  a 
value in the range -16777215 to 16777215 with Immediate type.
.pa
2.6.9   PC Relative

The PC relative type is assigned to symbols which refer to memory 
locations defined relative to the PC register.

The two letter abbreviation for PC relative type is PC.  Below is 
a listing format example:

  TEST1       0000123  PC

The PC relative type has the following form:

  <disp>  (PC)

where  <disp>  is a constant or expression which evaluates  to  a 
value in the range -16777215 to 16777215 with Immediate type.


2.6.10  Undefined

The  Assembler issues an error message if an undefined symbol  is 
found.
.pa
2.7  LOCATION COUNTER

The Assembler maintains five location counters of which only  one 
is active at any one time.  The five location counters correspond 
to  the  five segment types supported by  the  Assembler below:

  - program code relative
  - static base relative
  - frame pointer relative
  - stack pointer relative
  - immediate

When  the Assembler processes a segment change pseudo-op it saves 
the current location counter value and relocation type and enters 
the  new mode.  On exiting the new relocation mode  the  previous 
mode  and  location  counter are restored.  Up to  16  levels  of 
segment nesting are supported by the DSI-32 assembler.

A special symbol, $, is reserved by the Assembler to refer to the 
current  location  counter and relocation type.  The  symbol  may 
appear  alone  or  as a term in an expression (only  addition  or 
subtraction operators are allowed with the '$' symbol).

Examples:

  1.  FRED:   EQU  $
  2.  LENGTH: EQU  $ - FRED

In example 1,  $ specifies the current address.   The symbol FRED 
is assigned the current location counter value and type.

In  example 2,  the expression $ - FRED is assigned to the symbol 
LENGTH.
.pa
2.8  EXPRESSIONS

The  DSI-32 Assembler enables expressions to be evaluated and  be 
used  as operands for various  instructions.  Since  instructions 
expect particular operand types, the assembler tags the resultant 
expression value with a type.

The  following may be used as terms in expressions:   instruction 
operands,  constants,  symbols  and the location  counter  ('$'). 
Terms  of  a specific type may only appear with terms of  another 
specific type as described in section 2.8.2.

Operators   in   expressions  define   arithmetic   and   logical 
operations.  An operator has the following features:

   - An  operator's precedence level controls the order in  which 
     the assembler evaluates an expression.

   - An  operator  constrains the type of the term(s)  which  may 
     appear  in the expression.  It also constrains the resultant 
     type of the expression.

Table  2-1 lists all DSI-32 operators in order of precedence from 
lowest to highest.  The type and order of the terms which may  be 
used with certain operators are listed in Table 2-2.
.pa
                    TABLE 2-1.  OPERATOR PRECEDENCE
.cw 10
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Precedence  |	Operator | 	Name	  |     Operation		  |
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Unary Operators:							  |
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
|	1     |	   +     |  unary positive |  identity	  		  |
|	1     |	   -	 |  unary minus	  |  two's complement		  |
|	1     |	   ~	 |  complement	  |  one's complement		  |
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Binary Operators:							  |
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
|	2     |	   *	 |  multiply	  |  multiply 1st and 2nd terms   |
|	2     |	   /	 |  divide	  |  divide 1st by 2nd term	  |
|	2     |    %	 |  modulus	  |  remainder of 1st / 2nd term  |
|	2     |	   &	 |  logical AND	  |  bit AND of 1st and 2nd terms |
|	2     |	  <<	 |  shift left	  |  shift 1st by 2nd term;	  |
|	      |		 |		  |  emptied bits are zero-filled |
|	2     |	  >>	 |  shift right	  |  shift 1st by 2nd term;	  |
|	      |		 |		  |  emptied bits are zero-filled |
|	3     |	   +	 |  add		  |  add 1st and 2nd terms	  |
|	3     |	   -	 |  subtract	  |  subtract 1st and 2nd terms   |
|	3     |	   |	 |  logical or	  |  bit OR of 1st and 2nd terms  |
|	3     |	   ^	 |  exclusive or  |  bit exclusive OR of 1st and  |
|	      |		 |		  |  2nd terms			  |
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.pa
                   TABLE 2-2  TYPES AND OPERATORS

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
|  Unary operators:							  |
|									  |
|		Operator	Term1	Operation			  |
|									  |
|		   +		 %1	identity of %1			  |
|		   -		 %1	two's complement of %1		  |
|		   ~		 %1	one's complement of %1		  |
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
|  Binary operators:							  |
|									  |
|	Term1	Operator    Term2	Operation			  |
|	  %1	   *	      #2	multiply %1 by #2		  |
|	  %1	   /	      #2	divide %1 by #2			  |
|	  %1	   %	      #2	modulus of %1 divided by #2	  |
|	  %1	   &	      #2	bit-wise logical AND of %1 and #2 |
|	  %1	  <<	      #2	shift %1 left by #2 positions	  |
|	  %1	  >>	      #2	shift %1 right by #2 positions	  |
|									  |
|	  %1	   +	      #2	add %1 and #2			  |
|	  %1	   -	      #2	subtract #2 from %1		  | 
|	  %1	   -	      &2	subtract &2 from %1		  |
|									  |
|	  $1	   +	      #2	add $1 and #2			  |
|	  $1	   -	      #2	subtract #2 from $1		  |
|	  $1	   -	      &2	subtract &2 from $1		  |
|									  |
|	  %1	   |	      #2	bit-wise logical OR of %1 and #2  |
|	  %1	   ^	      #2	bit wise exclusive OR of %1 and #2|
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.cw 12
Notation:

#2   may be a term which has Immediate type.   It must appear  to 
     the right of the operator.

%1   may be a term which has either Immediate or Absolute type or 
     one  of the Relative types.   This term must appear  to  the      
     right  of  a   unary operator or to the  left  of  a  binary                
     operator.

$1   may be a term with External type.   It must appear  to  the      
     left of the operator.

&2   must  be a term which has the same type as the  first  term.  
     It must appear to the right of a binary operator.
.pa
2.8.1  Rules for Expressions

Expressions must follow the following rules:

 a)  Unary  operators precede single terms,  e.g.  the expression 
     ~(-1) is legal, but 7 ~(-1) is not.

 b)  Binary operators separate two terms, e.g. the expression 7+2 
     is legal, but 7+*2 is not.

 c)  Expressions  may  be  made  up  of  several  other   smaller 
     expressions.  Unary and binary operators may be used to link 
     up the smaller expressions,  e.g.  the two expressions "2+1" 
     and  "4+2"  may  be combined with a  division  operator  and 
     parentheses   to  obtain  the  single  compound   expression 
     "(2+1)/(4+2)".

 d)  Expressions are evaluated by three rules:

   - Parentheses.   Expressions  within  parentheses  are  always 
     evaluated first.  E.g.  the expression "16/8/2" evaluates to 
     "1", while the expression "16/(8/2)" evaluates to "4".

   - Precedence Groups.  An operator of a higher precedence group 
     will  cause the assembler to evaluate the terms  surrounding 
     that  operator  prior to terms surrounding an operator of  a 
     lower  precedence  whenever  parentheses  do  not  otherwise 
     control  the  evaluation order,  e.g the expression  "8+8/4" 
     evaluates  to "10",  but the expression "8/8+4  evaluates to 
     "5".

   - Left to Right Evaluation.  Expressions evaluate from left to 
     right  whenever  parentheses  or  precedence  rules  do  not 
     otherwise  determine evaluation order,  e.g.  the expression 
     "4*2/1"  evaluates  as  "8",   but  the  expression  "4/2*1" 
     evaluates to "2".


2.8.2  Types in Expressions

Expressions  with mixed types and operators follow certain  rules 
as outlined below:

1.   Expressions with Terms having Immediate Type.

     Terms  with Immediate Type may have any operator applied  to 
     them.  The resultant type is always Immediate.
.pa
     Examples:

     1.  23 * 7          result is 000000A1 IM
     2.  23 / 7          result is 00000003 IM
     3.  23 % 7          result is 00000002 IM
     4.  23 & 7          result is 00000007 IM
     5.  23 << 7         result is 00000B80 IM
     6.  23 >> 7         result is 00000000 IM
     7.  23 + 7          result is 0000001E IM
     8.  23 - 7          result is 00000010 IM
     9.  23 | 7          result is 00000017 IM
     10.  23 ^ 7          result is 00000010 IM

2.   Expressions  with  terms  Having Relative  or  Absolute  and 
     Immediate Types.

     Terms  with  relative  or  absolute  type  and  terms   with 
     immediate  type may have the following operators applied  to 
     them:  *,  /,  %, &, <<, >>, +, -, | and ^.  The operator is 
     applied  to  the first and the second terms and the type  of 
     the  first term is assigned to the result.  The  first  term 
     must  have  relative or absolute type while the second  term 
     must have Immediate type.

     Examples:

     1.  23(SB) * 7       result is  000000A1 SB
     2.  23(SB) / 7       result is  00000003 SB
     3.  23(SB) % 7       result is  00000002 SB
     4.  23(SB) & 7       result is  00000007 SB
     5.  23(SB) << 7      result is  00000B80 SB
     6.  23(SB) >> 7      result is  00000000 SB
     7.  23(SB) + 7       result is  0000001E SB
     8.  23(SB) - 7       result is  00000010 SB
     9.  23(SB) | 7       result is  00000017 SB
     10. 23(SB) ^ 7       result is  00000010 SB

3.   Expressions with Terms Having Relative or Absolute Type

     Terms with relative or absolute type may only be  subtracted 
     from terms of the same type.  The Immediate type is assigned 
     to the result.

     Example:

     1.  1(PC) - 7(PC)     result is FFFFFFFA IM
     2.  12(SB) - 4(SB)    result is 00000008 IM
     3.  15(FP) - 3(FP)    result is 0000000C IM
     4.  7(SP) - 3(SP)     result is 00000004 IM
.pa
4.   Expressions with Terms Having External and Immediate Type

     Terms with Immediate type may be added to or subtracted from 
     terms with external type. Note: only the offset is affected. 
     The external type is assigned to the result.

     Examples:

     1.  EXT(3)+12 + 4     result is 00000003 00000010 EX
     2.  EXT(12)+3 - 10    result is 0000000C FFFFFFF9 EX

5.   Expressions with Terms Having External Type

     Terms  with external type may be subtracted from each  other 
     only if they have the same Link Table number.  The Immediate 
     type is assigned to the result.

     Examples:

     1.  EXT(7)+ 3 - EXT(7)+12     result is FFFFFFF7 IM
     2.  EXT(12)+2 - EXT(12)-10    result is 0000000C IM
     3.  EXT(4) - EXT(4)           result is 00000000 IM


2.8.3  Length of Displacements

In the DSI-32 Assembly language,  the length of a displacement in 
an  instruction operand may be explicitly defined,  otherwise the 
Assembler will supply a default length.

The  length  of  an operand is specified by  appending  a  length 
specifier  to the displacement.   The following length specifiers 
are permitted:
     :B - byte displacement
     :W - word displacement (two byte)
     :D - double-word displacement (four bytes).

Following are the rules regarding length specifiers:

  1. Length specifiers appended to operands which evaluate to the 
     Immediate type are ignored by the assembler. This is because 
     the assembler knows the length of the value in all passes. 

  2. If  the  displacement  is an  expression  whose  terms  have 
     already  been  defined in previous statements the  Assembler 
     will  automatically calculate the correct length  specifier. 
     If  the programmer supplies a length specifier it must be no 
     smaller  than  the calculated length else an error  will  be 
     reported.
.pa
  3. If  the  displacement  is a symbol which has  not  yet  been 
     defined,  and no length specifier has been supplied a length 
     of  4 bytes will be assumed by the Assembler.  If  a  length 
     specifier  is  supplied  it  must be  no  smaller  than  the 
     required length, otherwise, an error results.

  4. If a length specifier is supplied for the first displacement 
     of  a memory relative operand,  it may appear anywhere after 
     the displacement,  but within the parentheses. The following 
     operands are treated equally by the assembler:

        5(10:W(FP))    5(10(FP):W)

  5. The assembler requires any length specifier that is appended 
     to  the second displacement of a memory relative operand  to 
     immediately follow the displacement.

        5:W(10(FP))

Examples:

  1.  ADDB   MON(FP):W, R7
  2.  CMPQB  2,(WEEK+3):B(SB)
  3.  SUBD   10(UP:B(SP)),R2

In  example 1,  the displacement for the frame memory operand  is 
one  word long.

In  example 2,  the displacement for the static memory operand is 
one  byte long.

In  example  3,  the  first  displacement for  the  stack  memory 
relative operand is one byte long.

